System Configuration
Grid (33 kV, 500 MVAsc)
→ Transformer (33 / 0.415 kV, 1 MVA, Z = 5%)
→ Bus (0.415 kV)
→ Cable (varied length and size)
→ Lump Load (varied from 0.3 MVA to 0.75 MVA)

Experiments Conducted
Case 1: Reduced Load
Load = 0.3 MVA
Cable Length = 50 m
Result: Voltage ≈ 99% (≈ 411 V)

Observation:
Low load resulted in minimal current flow and negligible voltage drop.

Case 2: Reduced Cable Length
Load = 0.75 MVA
Cable Length = 20 m
Result: Voltage ≈ 97.84% (≈ 406 V)

Observation:
Shorter cable reduced impedance, improving voltage at the load.

Case 3: Increased Cable Size
Load = 0.75 MVA
Cable Length = 50 m (larger conductor)
Result: Voltage ≈ 97%

Observation:
Increasing cable size reduced resistance, maintaining acceptable voltage despite longer distance.

Additional Observation (System Failure Case)
Load = 0.75 MVA
Cable Length = 50 m (smaller cable)
Result: Load flow did not converge

Interpretation:
High current through a high-impedance cable caused excessive voltage drop, leading to system instability.

Key Learnings
Voltage drop increases with load (current increase)
Voltage drop increases with cable length (higher impedance)
Larger cables reduce resistance and improve voltage stability
Systems can fail to converge when operating beyond physical limits
Acceptable voltage range: 95% – 105%

Core Principle:
Voltage Drop ∝ Current × Impedance

Conclusion
Voltage drop is a critical factor in power system design.
Proper selection of cable size, load level, and system configuration ensures stable and efficient operation.
